revision.text:
Polish nouns are classified as '''singular''' (name for one thing) or '''plural''' (name for more than one thing)
To make singular feminine nouns plural, look at the penultimate letter to decide what to change the '''-a''' to:
{| class="wikitable" ! Singular ! Plural ! Example |- | -ka, -ga | -ki, -gi | ''noga'' – ''nogi'' (leg – legs) |- | -ca, -ea, -ia, -ja, -la, -ża (-rza) | -ce, -ee, -ie, -je, -le, -że (-rze) | ''róża'' – ''róże'' (rose – roses) |- | -[everything else] + a | -[everything else] + y | ''torba – torby'' (bag – bags) |}
Remember that '''rz''' also sounds like '''ż''' * ''burza'' – ''burze'' (storm – storms)
To make neuter nouns plural, change the '''-o''', '''-e''', or '''-um''' to '''-a''' * ''okno'' – ''okna'' * ''muzeum'' – ''muzea'' The plurals of nouns ending in '''-ę''' are irregular and will not be covered at this time.
To make masculine nouns plural, look at the last letter. They follow similar rules to feminine nouns.
{| class="wikitable" ! Singular ! Plural ! Example |- | -k, -g | -ki, -gi | ''bok'' – ''boki'' (side – sides) |- | -c, -j, -l, -ż (-rz) | -ce, -je, -le, -że (-rze) | ''garaż'' – ''garaże'' (garage – garages) |- | -ć, -ń, -ś, -ź | -cie, -nie, -sie, -zie | ''koń'' – ''konie'' (horse – horse) |- | -[everything else] | -[everything else] + y | ''las – lasy'' (forest – forests) |}
